I think this dual-meaning for &#x27;after&#x27; is quite common, at least in Ireland and UK (and Australia). Here&#x27;s an example in lieu of a formal citation:<p>1. After getting dinner, Alice and Bob met friends at a local bar
- Purely temporal, one thing followed the other<p>2. After hearing Alice recommend her gym, Bob signed up for a membership.
- Causal (and temporal of course): because of the first thing, the second thing happened<p>You can disambiguate this in many ways, the most common in my experience is to make explicit the time<p>&quot;Darwin discovered the theory of evolution many years after studying finches on the Galápagos Islands&quot;
